# ~/.zshrc.secrets
#
# Local shell secrets. The baseline dot_zshrc.tmpl sources this file if it
# exists, so anything exported here is available in your interactive shells
# and in commands run from them (including editor integrations that inherit
# the shell environment).
#
# Safety rules:
#     - This file is owned by YOUR user. Do not commit it anywhere, even
#       to a private overlay repo. If you use an overlay repo for non-secret
#       shell snippets, keep secrets in ~/.zshrc.secrets, shared non-secret
#       exports in ~/.config/work/env.sh, and interactive-only helpers in
#       ~/.zsh/work.zsh (see zsh-work.zsh.example).
#     - `chmod 600 ~/.zshrc.secrets` so other local users cannot read it.
#     - Rotate any token that has ever landed in a file committed to any
#       repo, even briefly. A revoked token is still a leaked token.
#
# Examples (replace with your real values in the real overlay, never here):
#
# export GIT_HOST_TOKEN="<your-hosted-git-token>"
# export GITHUB_TOKEN="<your-github-pat>"
# export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="<your-anthropic-key>"
#
# # If a secret is machine-local (e.g. a 1Password Connect token), guard it
# # with a hostname check to avoid surprising yourself on another machine:
# if [[ "$(hostname -s)" == "<your-machine-hostname>" ]]; then
#     export SOME_LOCAL_ONLY_SECRET="<value>"
# fi
